Prudentia bids us regard time and circumstance, in so far as this is necessary for the attainment of moral ends, εὐταξία, in so far as our outward circumstances and the good opinion of our fellow·men are concerned. Cicero indicates the difference between εὐταξία and prudentio in the words: quae pertinent ad vere- cundiam et od eorum approbationem quibuscum vivimus.
